title: Anglesea Heath - Flora and Fauna
description: The Anglesea Heath surrounds the township of Anglesea. It extends north for approx 20 km, and west to Aireys Inlet.

items.title: Epacris impressa var. impressa
items.content_text: Mass displays of white Epacris impressa growing with pink Epacris in this SW corner of Anglesea Heath - see pic 4. In other places there are pink Epacris and white L. virgatus growing en masse but here L. virgatus seems to have been replaced by white Epacris.

items.title: Acacia suaveolens
items.content_text: Occasional mass flowering on roadsides, especially in gullies. Here plants were 2m+ along roadside, occasionally broken up with pink Epacris impressa.

items.title: Leucopogon virgatus var. virgatus
items.content_text: Mass displays of L. virgatus growing with pink (no white) Epacris impressa in this SW corner of Anglesea Heath. In other places there are pink and white Epacris growing en masse but here L. virgatus seems to have displaced white Epacris.

items.title: Epacris impressa var. impressa
items.content_text: Magnificent displays of Epacris in this SW corner of Anglesea Heath. At this location the Epacris were all red and mass flowering with Leucopogon virgatus, Acacia suaveolens and with Banksia marginata sprinked through.

items.title: Paropsisterna spp.
items.content_text: This is another Paropsisterna from the interlita group.  I am not sure yet how they fit together and which species is which.  This appears to be diurnal.  I saw this also at Aberfeldy.

items.title: Paropsisterna spp.
items.content_text: I have no ID to offer for this species.  It has definite similarities with P. atalanta which is mottled red but with the same black regions and found in the same location.  I have seen this only once

items.title: Paropsisterna hectica
items.content_text: This is Paropsisterna hectica. A golden/green leaf beetle, sometimes with a red pigment extending from the base of the elytra. This species occurs from NSW to Victoria. A Tasmanian species is golden, rather than green and called Paropsisterna aurea. The Tasmanian beetle is still considered a different species but they are quite identical to this golden one and probably all belong to Paropsisterna hectica and will become synonomized in due course. This is found on Snow Gum (White Sallee). Also found in Licola.

items.title: Paropsisterna hectica

The Tasmanian beetle is still considered a different species but they are quite identical to this golden one and probably all belong to Paropsisterna hectica and will become synonomized in due course. This is found on Snow Gum (White Sallee). Also found in Licola but they are green, not golden and the red flare was not noticed to occur in that population.

items.title: Paropsisterna atalanta
items.content_text: This is Paropsisterna atalanta.  A rotund and mottled leaf beetle feeding on Eucalyptus in the Anglesea heathland.  I have seen this in Gisborne and Eildon.  It is variable with black marks on the elytra at the base or the apex.

items.title: Hibbertia riparia
items.content_text: Grows to about 50cm high. Stiff, narrow greyish leaves vary in length and hairiness. Terminal pale to bright yellow five-petalled flowers are almost stalkless and are surrounded by leaf-like bracts.

Scaevola albida
items.content_text: Five petalled white to blue fan-shaped flowers. The crowded, oval leaves vary in size. They may be toothed, or have smooth margins.

items.title: Hibbertia sericea var. sericea s.s.
items.content_text: Stalkless flowers in terminal clusters among leaf-like bracts. Silky hairs cover the leaves.

items.title: Thysanotus patersonii
items.content_text: Has a fine leafless stem which twines loosely around other vegetation. Small mauve to violet flowers are about 1cm wide, and are borne singly at the end of short branches, on the flowering stem.

items.title: Leptospermum myrsinoides
items.content_text: A short spreading shrub. Has small leaves that turn inwards. Silky hairs grow on the calyx.

Leaves 3mm wide, almost flat, incurved from margins.
